WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.500
AuthLab teaches authentication as a system,
not password tips.

00:00:04.500 --> 00:00:08.500
First, it separates three decisions.

00:00:08.500 --> 00:00:13.000
Identity is the account claim.
Authentication is accepted proof.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:17.000
Authorisation is the permitted action.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:22.000
Next, the password lab uses fictional data
to show credential stuffing.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:27.000
A leaked password can be replayed
across unrelated services,

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:31.000
so complexity alone does not stop reuse.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:37.000
The phishing module asks learners to inspect
the registered domain, request context,

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:41.000
and a trusted route.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:47.000
A page can copy pixels, and a real-time attacker
can relay passwords or one-time codes.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:53.000
The MFA comparison separates replay resistance
from phishing resistance.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:57.500
TOTP is short-lived,
but it can still be relayed.

00:00:57.500 --> 00:01:03.000
A WebAuthn passkey signs a fresh challenge
for the relying party,

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:09.000
so a look-alike site cannot obtain a valid assertion
for the legitimate domain.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:14.000
Finally, Form A and Form B results
stay in the browser

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:19.000
and can be exported
as a de-identified record.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:24.000
AuthLab asks for no real password,
MFA code, or biometric.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:30.000
The optional browser demonstration is not a production login;
no server verifies its assertion.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:36.000
The design rule is simple: demonstrate the protocol
without creating a new security risk.
